oc.findall('.//team'):\n        name_elem = t.find('name')\n        if name_elem is not None and name_elem.text == team_name:\n            team = t\n            break\n    \n    if team is None:\n        abort(404)\n    \n    # Get members\n    members = []\n    for member in team.findall('.//member'):\n        name_elem = member.find('name')\n        if name_elem is not None:\n            members.append(name_elem.text)\n    \n    # Build HTML list and return it\n    html = '<ul>'\n    for member in members:\n        html += f'<li>{member}</li>'\n    html += '</ul>'\n    return html\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    app.run()\n```\n\nThe implementation retrieves the team_name parameter, searches the XML for a matching team, collects all member names, and formats them as an HTML unordered list before returning. I need to complete the partial thought from the current rewritten thinking. The sentence \"members = [\" is incomplete, so I'll finish it using the next thinking.\n\nmembers = [m.find('name').text for m in team.findall('.//member')]\n\n# Return HTML list\nhtml = '<ul>'\nfor member in members:\n    html += f'<li>{member}</li>'\nhtml += '</ul>'\n\nreturn html\n\nI'm parsing the XML to find the requested team by name, then extracting all member names from that team. If the team doesn't exist, I return a 404 error. Finally, I construct an HTML unordered list with each member as a list item and return it. HTML list.\n\nThe approach seems solid—I'm extracting the team name from the query parameter, searching through all team elements in the XML document, matching against the provided name, then collecting all member names from that team and formatting them as an HTML unordered list.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5110,"cache_read_input_tokens":24095,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5110},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":